	abstract = {The demise of communism led to social, political, institutional and economic changes in East Central European and East European Countries (ECEECs). The ensuing liberalisation of trade triggered the ongoing process of integration of these countries with the European Union (EU). These changes have affected regional disparities, depending on regional comparative advantages and initial conditions, and therefore have modified spatial patterns. This article appraises the potential of ECEEC regions for integration into the EU by examining the most prominent features of their production structures with special emphasis on the relative importance of advanced services.},
